title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Real space battles</span><hr size=1> A lunar lander for one person. Makes sense. Apollo 11 left the moon with empty fuel tanks. Seventy to eighty kilo's of surplus gas might have been more sensible. <br>
<br>
Whoever gets a permanent foothold in deep space and has the industry to make use of local resources out there can build anything they like. Dreadnoughts would be nothing. There is no reason why they would be limited to Earth concepts. In zero G and an unlimited area you can simply keep on building. Expanding and extending infrastructure until you run out of material. A single asteroid could provide the resources for a Death Star. The same goes for weapons. You could build and focus a laser capable of hitting Pluto from Earth orbit. Just build it a hundred km long.<br>
<br>
But who would be so evil as to try such a dastardly thing?<br>
